## Critical Flaws to Fix in Rebuild\
\
### 1. CATASTROPHIC LAYOUT BUG \'97 Desktop White Gap\
The Carrd site uses `display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center` on the `.site-wrapper`, which vertically centers all content in the viewport. Combined with a very tall page (4400px+) and a giant 800px circular image, this creates MASSIVE white gaps between sections on desktop. Users scrolling past the second section encounter hundreds of pixels of pure white emptiness before reaching any content. Most desktop users will assume the page is over and leave \'97 never seeing the screening descriptions, pricing, or booking buttons. This is likely the single biggest conversion killer.\
\
### 2. No Navigation\
There is no header, no nav bar, no anchor links, no way to jump to sections. On a very long single-page site, this means users must scroll endlessly. There is no sticky header with a "Book Now" CTA always visible.\
\
### 3. No Clear CTA Hierarchy\
The first CTA a user sees is a phone number. The "Book Now" buttons are buried far below the fold \'97 past the white gap, past all the screening descriptions, past the location info. By the time a user scrolls to pricing, they've already likely bounced. The booking action should be prominent and above the fold.\
\
### 4. Weak Social Proof / Trust Signals\
There are no testimonials, no reviews, no "trusted by X patients", no doctor credentials, no certifications, no insurance info, no before/after statistics. For a health service, trust is everything. The site has zero trust-building elements.\
\
### 5. Minimal SEO\
The meta description is only 5 words ("Ultrasound Screenings in Las Vegas"). There are no structured data / schema markup. No keyword optimization. No blog/content. Only one H1, only one H2. No local SEO optimization beyond the address text.\
\
### 6. No Urgency or Scarcity\
There's nothing compelling someone to book NOW vs later. No limited-time pricing, no "only X slots left this Saturday", no mention of why early detection matters with statistics.\
\
### 7. Image Sizes Not Optimized\
The hero image is 804x804 and displayed as a massive circle that dominates the entire viewport. The small icon thumbnails are 426x425 but displayed much smaller. Images lack proper alt text (all empty strings). No WebP format. No lazy loading.\
\
### 8. Poor Information Architecture\
The screening descriptions and pricing are separated by location info, creating a disjointed flow. Users read about screenings, then see a location, then see prices \'97 they can't easily compare what they're getting for their money while reading the screening descriptions.\
\
### 9. Form UX Issues\
The contact form has both "Comment" and "Message" fields \'97 redundant and confusing. The form has no phone number field despite being a phone-call-heavy business. No clear indication of what happens after submission.\
\
### 10. Mobile Responsiveness Issues\
While technically responsive, the Carrd site clips text at narrow widths (below ~480px) and the hero heading gets cut off. The massive circular image doesn't scale gracefully on small screens.\
\
### 11. No Footer\
No footer with business hours, address, phone, social links, or legal pages (privacy policy, terms).\
\
### 12. "Las Vegas" Repeated Redundantly\
The heading says "Las Vegas Signal View Screenings" \'97 the city name shouldn't be in the brand/heading; it should be in a location badge or subtext.\
\
